---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import decodedAnatomy from "../../assets/projects/voyager/decoded-anatomy.png";
import decodedCalibrationCircle from "../../assets/projects/voyager/decoded-calibration-circle.png";
import decodedEarth from "../../assets/projects/voyager/decoded-earth.png";
import decodedFish from "../../assets/projects/voyager/decoded-fish.png";
import decodedMeasurementDiagram from "../../assets/projects/voyager/decoded-measurement-diagram.png";
import decodedRecordInstructions from "../../assets/projects/voyager/decoded-record-instructions.png";
import goldenRecordCover from "../../assets/projects/voyager/golden-record-cover.jpg";
import spectrogramFirstFrames from "../../assets/projects/voyager/spectrogram-first-frames.png";
import MermaidDiagram from "../../components/MermaidDiagram.astro";
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const decodePipelineDiagram = `flowchart LR
  wav["Golden Record WAV"]
  waveform["Waveform navigation"]
  window["Decode window"]
  sync["Line sync detection"]
  slant["Slant correction"]
  resample["Anti aliased resampling"]
  normalize["Percentile normalization"]
  image["Decoded image"]
  export["PNG export"]

  wav --> waveform
  waveform --> window
  window --> sync
  sync --> slant
  slant --> resample
  resample --> normalize
  normalize --> image
  image --> export`;

const workerDiagram = `sequenceDiagram
  participant UI as egui interface
  participant Queue as Worker queue
  participant Decode as Decode worker
  participant Diagnostics
  participant Result as Result cache

  UI->>Queue: Submit decode or diagnostic job
  Queue->>Decode: Run latest requested window
  Decode->>Diagnostics: Emit sync stats spectrogram segments
  Decode-->>Result: Store image and metadata
  UI->>Queue: Cancel stale work when controls change
  Queue-->>Decode: Stop old job
  Result-->>UI: Show only current result
  Diagnostics-->>UI: Explain why the image looks that way`;
---

<Layout
	title="Voyager Golden Record Explorer"
	description="Voyager Golden Record Explorer is Rebecca Clair's Rust/egui signal-processing application for recovering NASA Golden Record images from audio, with decoding, diagnostics, visualization, and export tools."
>
	<main class="project-page">
		<a class="back-link" href="/projects/">← Projects</a>
		<article class="content project-detail">
			<p class="eyebrow">Rust · Signal processing · Diagnostic tooling</p>
			<h1>Voyager Golden Record Explorer</h1>
			<p class="lede">
				Voyager Golden Record Explorer is a Rust/egui application for recovering
				the images encoded in NASA's Voyager Golden Record audio. It turns noisy
				analog source material into inspectable, adjustable, exportable image
				reconstructions, with diagnostics for understanding what the signal is
				doing rather than just hoping the decode looks right.
			</p>

			<h2>The problem</h2>
			<p>
				The Golden Record images are encoded as audio, so reconstruction is part
				signal-processing problem and part interface problem. You need to detect
				sync, correct slant, normalize uncertain analog levels, inspect the
				waveform, and iterate quickly enough that exploration does not become a
				pile of one-off scripts.
			</p>

			<h2>What I built</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>
					A baseband slow-scan video decoding pipeline with per-line sync
					detection, slant correction, anti-aliased resampling, polarity and gamma
					controls, and percentile normalization.
				</li>
				<li>
					Audio-device-clock anchored playback, zero-copy WAV loading, waveform
					navigation, sync markers, live decode windows, and PNG export for large
					audio assets.
				</li>
				<li>
					CLI and batch diagnostics for reproducible analysis: decode,
					spectrogram generation, sync detection, signal classification,
					statistics, segmentation, and excerpt carving.
				</li>
				<li>
					Worker orchestration with queue-depth tracking, health monitoring,
					restart logic, cancellation, stale-result suppression, and independent
					forward-model validation.
				</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>How it works</h2>
			<p>
				I built the explorer as an interactive decoding bench rather than a single
				“convert this WAV to an image” script. The audio is loaded once, navigated
				through a waveform view, and decoded through a baseband slow-scan pipeline
				that looks for line sync, estimates line boundaries, corrects slant,
				resamples into pixels, and normalizes the result into an image you can
				actually inspect.
			</p>
			<p>
				The controls exist because the source material is analog and imperfect. You
				can adjust polarity, gamma, normalization, sync interpretation, and decode
				windows while seeing the result change. The diagnostics mirror the UI path:
				decode runs, spectrograms, sync detection, segmentation, statistics, and
				excerpt carving all produce evidence about what the signal is doing.
			</p>

			<MermaidDiagram
				title="Decode pipeline"
				caption="The audio is treated as an inspectable signal path, not a black-box converter."
				chart={decodePipelineDiagram}
			/>

			<MermaidDiagram
				title="Responsive exploration loop"
				caption="Long-running decode and diagnostic work stays behind a queue so the UI can remain interactive while stale work is cancelled."
				chart={workerDiagram}
			/>

			<h2>Visual evidence from the record</h2>
			<p>
				These are not mockups. The cover image comes from the project assets, and
				the decoded frames below were generated from the local Golden Record audio
				with the project's own CLI. They are imperfect in the useful way: the sync
				stripes, slant, analog noise, and contrast decisions are visible, so the
				page shows the actual reconstruction problem instead of pretending the
				output falls out cleanly.
			</p>

			<div class="voyager-visuals">
				<figure class="record-cover">
					<Image
						src={goldenRecordCover}
						alt="The Voyager Golden Record cover diagram"
						widths={[480, 760, 980]}
						sizes="(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 760px"
					/>
					<figcaption>
						The Golden Record cover is the instruction manual: playback speed,
						image timing, calibration, and where Voyager came from.
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure class="spectrogram">
					<Image
						src={spectrogramFirstFrames}
						alt="Spectrogram of the first decoded Voyager Golden Record image frames"
						widths={[480, 760, 980]}
						sizes="(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 760px"
					/>
					<figcaption>
						A spectrogram over the first decoded frames, with frequency markers,
						used to sanity-check the signal rather than just stare at pixels and
						hope.
					</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>

			<div class="decoded-grid" aria-label="Decoded Voyager Golden Record frames">
				<figure>
					<Image
						src={decodedCalibrationCircle}
						alt="Decoded Voyager Golden Record calibration circle"
						widths={[320, 480, 640]}
						sizes="(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 320px"
					/>
					<figcaption>Calibration circle</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure>
					<Image
						src={decodedMeasurementDiagram}
						alt="Decoded Voyager Golden Record measurement diagram"
						widths={[320, 480, 640]}
						sizes="(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 320px"
					/>
					<figcaption>Measurement diagram</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure>
					<Image
						src={decodedEarth}
						alt="Decoded Voyager Golden Record image of Earth"
						widths={[320, 480, 640]}
						sizes="(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 320px"
					/>
					<figcaption>Earth frame</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure>
					<Image
						src={decodedAnatomy}
						alt="Decoded Voyager Golden Record anatomical image"
						widths={[320, 480, 640]}
						sizes="(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 320px"
					/>
					<figcaption>Anatomy frame</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure>
					<Image
						src={decodedFish}
						alt="Decoded Voyager Golden Record fish image"
						widths={[320, 480, 640]}
						sizes="(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 320px"
					/>
					<figcaption>Fish frame</figcaption>
				</figure>
				<figure>
					<Image
						src={decodedRecordInstructions}
						alt="Decoded Voyager Golden Record instruction diagram"
						widths={[320, 480, 640]}
						sizes="(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 320px"
					/>
					<figcaption>Instruction diagram</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</div>

			<h2>How it achieves the goal</h2>
			<p>
				The goal is not just to get a recognizable Golden Record image once. The goal
				is to make reconstruction explainable and repeatable. The app achieves that
				by tying visual exploration to reproducible analysis: every promising image
				can be traced back to the sync choices, window, normalization, and decode
				parameters that produced it.
			</p>
			<p>
				The worker system keeps that exploration responsive. Long-running decodes and
				diagnostics run behind queue-depth tracking, cancellation, stale-result
				suppression, health checks, and restart logic, so the interface stays usable
				while the signal-processing work happens underneath. It is a tiny lab bench
				for a beautiful, weird artifact from deep-space history, which is exactly my
				kind of nonsense.
			</p>
		</article>
	</main>
</Layout>

<style lang="scss">
	.project-page {
		max-width: 980px;
	}

	.back-link {
		display: inline-block;
		margin-bottom: 1rem;
		color: rgb(var(--accent));
	}

	.project-detail {
		padding-bottom: 2rem;
	}

	.eyebrow {
		margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
		color: var(--grey-mid);
		text-transform: uppercase;
		letter-spacing: 0.08em;
		font-size: 0.85rem;
	}

	h1 {
		font-size: 2.4rem;
		margin-top: 0;
	}

	.lede {
		font-size: 1.2rem;
		color: var(--color-fg-copy);
	}

	.voyager-visuals,
	.decoded-grid {
		display: grid;
		gap: 1rem;
		margin: 1.5rem 0;

		figure {
			margin: 0;
			padding: 0.75rem;
			border: 1px solid rgba(var(--accent), 20%);
			border-radius: var(--border-radius-base);
			background: #fff;
		}

		img {
			display: block;
			width: 100%;
			height: auto;
			border-radius: calc(var(--border-radius-base) * 0.75);
			background: var(--black);
		}

		figcaption {
			margin-top: 0.6rem;
			color: var(--color-fg-copy);
			font-size: 0.95rem;
			line-height: 1.35;
		}
	}

	.voyager-visuals {
		grid-template-columns: minmax(220px, 0.7fr) minmax(320px, 1.3fr);
		align-items: start;
	}

	.spectrogram {
		align-self: center;
	}

	.decoded-grid {
		grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(220px, 1fr));
	}

	@media (max-width: 760px) {
		.voyager-visuals {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		}
	}
</style>
